feature_description: We collected a set of 15 nouns with oblique stems in sonorant in attributive form. The maps show the sonorant that is present in an oblique stem formant: /r/ (value: R, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR), /l/ (value: L, e. g. *naʁ-ul-dɨ* teardrop-OBL-ATTR), /j/ (value: J, e. g. *naʁ-uji-d* teardrop-OBL-ATTR) or NO CONSONANT, if there is none.
name: Сара

feature_title: Presence of palatalization in oblique stems with a sonorant
feature_description: We collected a set of 15 nouns with oblique stems in sonorant in attributive form. We distinguish between soft and hard stems. Soft stems are morphophonologically palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with front vowels /e/, /i/ (value: SOFT, e. g. *ǯʷel-ir-dɨ* sheaf-OBL-ATTR). Hard stems are morphophonologically non-palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with non-front vowels /ɨ/, /a/ (value: HARD, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR). The maps show the variation in stem type.
name: Сара

Hard stems are morphophonologically non-palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with non-front vowels /ɨ/, /a/ (value: HARD, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR). The maps show the variation in stem type.
name: тажир

Soft stems are morphophonologically palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with front vowels /e/, /i/ (value: SOFT, e. g. *ǯʷel-ir-dɨ* sheaf-OBL-ATTR). Hard stems are morphophonologically non-palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with non-front vowels /ɨ/, /a/ (value: HARD, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR). The maps show the variation in stem type.
name: Индира

feature_description: We collected a set of 15 nouns with oblique stems in sonorant in attributive form. The maps show the sonorant that is present in an oblique stem formant: /r/ (value: R, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR), /l/ (value: L, e. g. *naʁ-ul-dɨ* teardrop-OBL-ATTR), /j/ (value: J, e. g. *naʁ-uji-d* teardrop-OBL-ATTR) or NO CONSONANT, if there is none.
name: Индира

feature_description: We collected a set of 15 nouns with oblique stems in sonorant in attributive form. We distinguish between soft and hard stems. Hard stems are morphophonologically non-palatalized, they select oblique stem formants with non-front vowels /ɨ/, /a/ (value: HARD, e. g. *git-ɨr-dɨ* cat-OBL-ATTR). The maps show the variation in stem type.
name: Муслимат

feature_description: We elicited the context with a personal lative construction: ‘Come to Rasul's (place) in the evening’. The map shows the marking on the noun ‘Rasul’. The attested variants include: case markers *-χda* / *-χdɨ* / *-χd*, *-k* (attested only in Khnov), *-χdal* (attested with only one consultant, in Khnov) and noun in attributive with a postposition — *-dɨ bejda* (attested only in Kiche).
name: Лейла

feature_description: We elicited the context with a personal essive (chezative, being at X’s place) construction: ‘Rasul lives at Magomed’s (place)’. The map shows the marking on the noun ‘Magomed’. The attested variants include: case markers — *-xʷan*, *-χda*, *-k*, noun phrases — *-dɨ χal(a)* ‘at X’s house’ and *-dɨ ǯigi(j)* ‘at X's place’. In Shinaz for some speakers it is possible to employ *ǯigi(j)* without dependent attributive marker *-dɨ*.

The attested variants include: case markers *-χdaː*, *-qla* / *-χla*, *-kla* / *-klʲa*, *-aːla* and the noun in attributive with a postposition — *-dɨ ǯigijaː* / *-d ǯigijaː*, *-d ǯigijaːla*. In one case in Shinaz the postposition *ǯigijaː* is attached directly to the absolutive form. Noun phrase *-d χalaː* ‘from one’s house’ is also attested once (Amsar).
name: Тагир
schooling: Kufa до 4 класса, потом в Рутуле
